snippet.textDisplay: When I lived in Manila I went up to Taal/Tagaytay at least a couple of times a month. It's still a breathtaking place, despite the over-development (they even have a Buffalo Wild Wings near the carter- the only one I've seen outside the US). The eternal spring climate up there makes the flora just incredible. The garden centres have every type of plant/flower and orchid. Every plant pot is home to giant toad, like the one in Pan's Labyrinth.  I took all my Irish aunts to stay in the villas at magical Sonya's Garden, but we didn't get a damn wink of sleep due to the nocturnal frog cacophony- the loudest of which sounded like mobile phones ringing ALL night. My aunt from Cork even got up to search high and low for the phone.  I always thought it odd that Taal volcano was marketed as the 'Philippines' Smallest Volcano' when the lake's island is just the most recent vent of an underlying SUPER VOLCANO. The entire giant lake (the only home to the endemic and beloved Tawilis fish) and surrounding hills are all part of a massive crater. If THAT wakes up then god help Manila.
